do instrumental activities of daily living predict dementia at 1- and 2-year follow-up?
\boxed{}
Based on the retrieved evidence, instrumental activities of daily living (IADLs) are indeed reliable predictors of dementia within 1- to 2-year follow-ups, supported by consistent reports that IADL impairments appear early in Alzheimer’s disease and other dementias, often preceding more severe functional declines. While self-report bias and instrument sensitivity vary, longitudinal studies confirm that declining IADL performance—such as managing finances or medications—is strongly correlated with subsequent dementia development, making them valuable early warning signals despite methodological limitations.
\boxed{\text{A}}

